  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does GST Bill will work?",
  "response": "The Goods and Services Tax (GST) Bill, which established the GST system in India, aims to simplify and unify the indirect tax regime across the country. Here's a basic overview of how the GST system works:\n\n1. **Unified Tax System**: GST consolidates various central and state taxes into a single tax, applicable uniformly across India. Taxes like Central Excise Duty, Service Tax, Value Added Tax (VAT), Octroi, and others are subsumed under GST.\n\n2. **Tax Structure**: GST is divided into three main categories:\n   - **Central GST (CGST)**: Levied by the central government on intra-state transactions.\n   - **State GST (SGST)**: Levied by state governments on intra-state transactions.\n   - **Integrated GST (IGST)**: Levied by the central government on inter-state transactions.\n\n3. **Tax Rates**: GST is applied at different rates based on the type of goods or services. The rates are generally categorized into slabs: 0%, 5%, 12%, 18%, and 28%. Some items may attract cess in addition to the GST.\n\n4. **Input Tax Credit (ITC)**: Businesses can claim an Input Tax Credit for the GST paid on their purchases, which can be set off against the GST they collect on sales. This helps avoid the cascading effect of taxes.\n\n5. **Compliance and Filing**: Registered businesses must file monthly returns detailing their sales, purchases, and the GST collected and paid. Quarterly and annual returns may also be required.\n\n6. **Invoice and Billing**: All GST invoices must contain specific information, including the GSTIN (GST Identification Number) of the supplier and purchaser, tax amounts, HSN (Harmonized System of Nomenclature) codes, and more. Proper invoicing is vital for claiming the Input Tax Credit and maintaining compliance.\n\n7. **GST Council**: The GST Council, comprising members from the central and state governments, oversees the regulation and administration of GST, including decisions on tax rates, exemptions, and policy changes.\n\n8. **Registration**: Businesses with a turnover exceeding a certain threshold must register for GST. There are provisions for voluntary registration for smaller enterprises.\n\n9. **Reverse Charge Mechanism**: In certain defined cases, the GST on services or goods is payable by the recipient instead of the supplier, known as the reverse charge mechanism.\n\n10. **E-Way Bill**: For the transport of goods exceeding a certain value, businesses must generate an e-way bill, which helps track the movement of goods and prevent tax evasion.\n\nOverall, GST aims to create a more efficient and streamline tax system, reduce tax evasion, and create a more predictable and transparent tax environment.",
